12. Glossary
1. What is private credit? (Plain English)
Think of private credit as a shadow mortgage market for businesses. Instead of companies borrowing from banks or issuing public bonds that anyone can buy on an exchange, they borrow directly from specialist funds — usually in deals that are negotiated privately, never traded, and marked to their own internal models rather than a live market price.

Simple analogy
Imagine a bank that lends money to risky small businesses, but instead of being regulated like a bank, it operates like a hedge fund. It raises money from pension funds and insurance companies, promises quarterly returns, and says "you can withdraw — but maybe not all at once." Now imagine nobody can see inside the loan book except the fund itself, and prices are set by an internal spreadsheet rather than a market. That's private credit.

The vehicles that hold these loans are called Business Development Companies (BDCs). Some are publicly traded (you can buy ARCC or OBDC on the NYSE). Many are "non-traded" — sold to wealthy retail investors and institutions, but with no live market price. The non-traded ones are where most of the current stress is concentrated.

Why private credit looks attractive (or did)
Private credit loans typically yield 9–11%, versus 5–6% for investment grade bonds. The "extra" return compensates for three things: (1) illiquidity — you can't easily sell the loan; (2) complexity — the deal is bespoke and hard to evaluate; and (3) credit risk — the borrowers are too small or risky for banks. For a decade, this tradeoff worked well. The critical caveat, documented by NBER research in 2026, is that the "low volatility" private credit advertised was partially fake — a product of marking loans at internal models that didn't update with market reality, not genuine stability.

Key terms you need to know before reading further
NAV (Net Asset Value)
The book value of a fund's assets minus its liabilities, per share. If a BDC has $100 of loans and $40 of debt, NAV = $60. If the stock trades at $45, it's at a 25% discount to NAV — the market believes the loans are worth less than stated.
PIK (Payment In Kind)
When a borrower can't pay cash interest, they "pay" by adding more debt to what they owe. It's a warning sign — like a credit card where you defer payments by borrowing more. PIK ratio = % of total interest income received as additional debt rather than cash.
ICR (Interest Coverage Ratio)
EBITDA ÷ interest expense. A ratio of 2.0x means the company earns twice what it pays in interest. Below 1.0x means the company is technically insolvent on an interest basis — it can't cover its own interest payments from operations.
BDC (Business Development Company)
A regulated fund structure created by Congress in 1980 to finance small businesses. BDCs can borrow up to 1× their equity (100% leverage cap under 1940 Act). Publicly traded BDCs must disclose every loan quarterly. Non-traded BDCs offer periodic redemptions but no live price discovery.
LTV (Loan-to-Value)
The loan amount as a percentage of the borrower's total enterprise value. Blackstone's software loans average 37% LTV, meaning 63% of the company's value would need to evaporate before Blackstone loses a dollar. Compare to subprime mortgages in 2008, which were often 90–100% LTV.
SOFR
The benchmark interest rate that replaced LIBOR. Private credit loans are usually "SOFR + 5–6%." When the Fed raises rates, SOFR rises, and the borrower's interest bill automatically increases — no renegotiation needed. This floating-rate structure is good for lenders in rising-rate environments and catastrophic for over-leveraged borrowers.
Gating / Redemption Gate
When too many investors try to withdraw at once, a non-traded BDC can cap redemptions — e.g., only honor 5% of the fund's total shares per quarter. Investors who asked to redeem 40.7% (as with Blue Owl's OTIC on April 2) receive only 5%. The rest stays locked in.
CDX.NA.HY
A derivatives index that tracks the credit risk of 100 high-yield US companies. Buying protection on this index (paying the spread) profits when corporate credit stress rises and spreads widen. Think of it as buying insurance on a basket of risky corporate debt.
2. How did private credit get so big?
The short answer: regulation created it. After the 2008 financial crisis, regulators imposed Basel III capital requirements and the Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR) on banks. These rules made it expensive for banks to hold leveraged middle-market loans on their balance sheets — the capital charges were simply too high relative to returns. Banks retreated. Private credit funds stepped in.

BIS researchers (Doerr, Gelos & Pursiainen, February 2026) proved this causally using a natural experiment: US counties where more LCR-constrained banks operated saw significantly more private credit growth after the rule was introduced. The effect was comparable in magnitude to the capital shock from stress tests. Put simply: private credit is a $1.7 trillion regulatory arbitrage.

Why this matters for the trade
The current administration is now rolling back those same regulations — LCR interpretive FAQs were rescinded February 10, 2026. Basel III Endgame has already been significantly softened. If banks can re-enter middle-market lending, the structural driver of private credit growth partially reverses. Every alt-manager equity valuation assumes 14% AUM CAGR. If the real rate is 5–7%, those valuations are structurally impaired regardless of the default cycle.

The Apollo-Athene flywheel made it bigger still. Apollo acquired Athene (a life insurance company) and used insurance policyholder deposits — money people put aside for retirement — to fund private credit deals. This gave them a permanent, cheap source of capital. Every major private credit firm has replicated this model. As a result, nearly a third of the $6 trillion sitting in US insurance company portfolios is now allocated to private credit sub-asset classes. Retail savers are far more exposed to this market than their account statements suggest.

