4. The three simultaneous shocks
Shock 1 — Iran war and rate reversal
Operation Epic Fury (Feb 28, 2026) — the US–Israel strikes on Iran — closed the Strait of Hormuz to commercial traffic. The Strait carries 38% of global seaborne crude and 20% of global LNG. Brent crude went from $70 to over $100 in weeks. This injected inflation into an already-strained US economy (GDP growth revised down to 0.7% in Q4 2025; unemployment at 4.4%).

The Fed, which was expected to cut twice in 2026, is now 19% likely to hike instead. For private credit borrowers — almost all of whom pay SOFR + 5–6% — this is a direct cash flow hit with no hedge. A 50bp rate increase adds $500M of annual interest expense to every $100B of floating-rate private credit.

Shock 2 — AI disrupting the biggest borrower sector
Software companies account for roughly 25% of direct lending portfolios. These loans were underwritten on Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR) multiples during 2020–2022, not EBITDA coverage. The thesis: SaaS businesses have sticky subscription revenue and high switching costs. That thesis is breaking: AI agents can now replicate what enterprise SaaS products do, at lower cost, reducing the "stickiness" that justified the lending.

BIS research (Aldasoro, Doerr & Rees, Jan 2026) shows AI investment has been partly financed by private credit. The AI sector is now in a circular financing loop — AI firms borrow to build, use those funds to buy from each other, which validates more AI investment, which requires more borrowing. Equity prices have "run far ahead of debt market pricing," per the BIS. If AI earnings disappoint, the debt doesn't disappear.

UBS stress scenario: 13–15% default rate on software-exposed private credit portfolios in an aggressive AI disruption scenario.

Shock 3 — The BDC liability maturity wall
BDCs borrow from banks to juice returns (back leverage). Approximately $12.7B of their own unsecured bonds mature in 2026 — up 73% versus 2025. They need to refinance this at a moment when: (a) their assets are being marked down; (b) their income is being impaired by PIK loans and non-accruals; and (c) their bank credit lines are being tightened. JPMorgan preemptively marked down software loans in March 2026, directly compressing BDC borrowing capacity.

This is the mechanism that converts a liquidity problem into a solvency problem: can't refinance → must sell assets → at a loss → marks fall further → borrowing base shrinks → forced to sell more. Each lap of that loop is tighter than the last.

5. The causal chain — how stress spreads step by step
This is the part most write-ups skip. Here is the mechanism in order:

Step 1 — Borrowers miss payments or go PIK
A mid-market SaaS company with $200M of private credit debt sees its ARR eroded by AI competition. It can't service cash interest. The lender agrees to PIK — the $10M annual interest payment is rolled into the principal. The BDC now has a $210M loan instead of $200M, but no cash came in. PIK income rises, cash income falls.
Step 2 — BDC marks the loan down
The BDC's valuation committee, advised by a third-party firm, marks the loan from $200M to $170M — it now believes full recovery is unlikely. NAV per share drops. Public BDC stock drops. Non-traded BDC investors read the quarterly report, get nervous, and submit redemption requests.
Step 3 — Redemption requests hit the gate
The fund receives withdrawal requests for 20–40% of its assets in a single quarter (as happened with Blue Owl OTIC: 40.7%). It can only honor 5% under its gate. Investors who wanted out are stuck. News of the gate spreads. More investors submit requests — not because they believe the portfolio is bad, but because they want to beat the next gate. The self-fulfilling dynamic begins.
Step 4 — BDC must sell assets or tighten
To fund any redemptions, the BDC sells loans in the secondary market. Private credit loans have almost no secondary market liquidity — there is no stock exchange for them. A forced seller gets 80–90 cents on the dollar. This sale is an observable market transaction that confirms the loan is worth less than NAV. More marks come down across the industry.
Step 5 — Banks tighten credit lines
BDCs borrow from banks against their loan portfolios ("back leverage"). The bank's credit line is tied to asset values — if the portfolio falls in value, the available credit shrinks. JPMorgan's March 2026 markdowns of software loans compressed BDC borrowing bases immediately. The BDC now has less money to lend, which means: fewer new deals, higher spreads demanded, and the middle market tightens.
Step 6 — Insurance companies sit on hidden losses
Apollo's Athene, KKR's Global Atlantic, and FNF's F&G hold private credit at amortised cost — they never mark to market. Their portfolio may be worth 10% less than stated, but nobody knows. The loss only surfaces when they must sell (unlikely) or when regulatory capital tests catch it (slow). The solvency concern is real but the timeline is years, not months.
Step 7 — Stocks and broad credit reprice
Alt-manager stocks drop because fee revenues fall with AUM. Public credit spreads widen because BDC forced selling hits the broadly syndicated loan (BSL) market. Wider credit spreads mean higher borrowing costs for all leveraged companies, compressing equity multiples. Historically, 100bp of credit spread widening correlates to 8–10% of equity multiple compression on the S&P 500.
The crucial nuance (from Chernenko & Scharfstein, Harvard/NBER)
Harvard stress tests show: if BDCs CAN sell loans, zero funds default on bank credit lines even in a GFC-equivalent shock. If they CANNOT sell (contractual restrictions or no buyer), 20–35% of funds enter technical default. The entire systemic risk question is binary: loan sellability. That's why the thin secondary market is the key vulnerability — not leverage or capitalisation.

6. The model and the math
The borrowing-base amplifier (plain English first)
Banks lend to BDCs against the value of their loan portfolios, typically at 75 cents per dollar of assets (a 25% haircut). When a BDC's loans get marked down, the bank automatically reduces the credit line. This forces the BDC to repay debt. To repay debt, it must either raise equity (hard in a stressed market) or sell loans (into an illiquid market). Every dollar of markdown forces 67 cents of forced deleveraging. That deleveraging hits the loan market, which pushes prices lower, which triggers more markdowns. This is the feedback loop.

Given: A = BDC total assets D = bank debt outstanding δ = bank's advance rate haircut (typically 1.5×, meaning lend against A/1.5) Credit line constraint: A ≥ δ · D → D = A/δ When assets fall by ΔA (a markdown): New debt capacity: D' = (A − ΔA)/δ Forced debt reduction: ΔD = ΔA/δ → At δ = 1.5: every $1 of markdown forces $0.67 of forced asset sales → $14B BDC loan sales at 85¢ recovery = $2.1B immediate loss + spread widening → BDCs hold $143B of leveraged loans — more than all dedicated loan funds ($120B) → This exceeds the secondary market's absorption capacity at par
