7. The AI loop nobody is talking about
Here is the dimension that connects the AI disruption story to the private credit story in a way that is not yet widely understood. BIS Bulletin 120 (Aldasoro, Doerr & Rees, January 2026) documents that AI investment is surging as a share of GDP and has already become a meaningful contributor to economic growth. But it also flags a tension: equity prices have run far ahead of debt market pricing, and the sustainability of the AI boom hinges on AI firms meeting very high earnings expectations.

The ScienceDirect paper on "AI, private credit, and financial bubbles" introduces the concept of the financial ouroboros: Nvidia, OpenAI, Oracle, AMD, and Microsoft engage in reciprocal investment and procurement relationships — they borrow from private credit, invest in each other, and sell to each other. Capital circulates within a partially closed network. This inflates balance sheets and valuation metrics without corresponding external demand validation. It's a circular structure: AI investment justifies AI investment because the customers are also the investors.

Why this matters for private credit specifically
Private credit financed a large chunk of AI infrastructure — data centres, GPU leasing, cloud capacity. If AI earnings disappoint (i.e., the external demand that would justify the circular investment does not materialise), the debt does not disappear. Private credit lenders holding AI infrastructure loans face the same binary as SaaS lenders: asset-light collateral, high leverage, and a business model whose viability depends on an earnings trajectory that equity markets have already priced in optimistically.

The practical implication: the bull case for data-centre private credit (used as the "safe harbour" in the investment thesis) depends on AI capex being validated by revenue. The BIS explicitly says this is the critical uncertainty. Asset-backed finance against AI infrastructure is safer than ARR loans, but not immune.

