The balanced view — what the best evidence actually says
NBER research by Matvos, Piskorski & Seru (March 2026, using comprehensive fund-level data) shows private credit funds carry 65–80% equity capital — six times better capitalised than banks — and have no maturity mismatch (fund lives of 10–12 years, loans of 5–7 years). Blackstone's own stress test: even at 10% defaults and 50% recovery (worse than GFC), the annual return drag is only ~150bp — a 9% yielding fund returns ~7.5%. That's not a crisis. The ARCC-vs-OBDC trade is about execution and manager quality, not about the asset class blowing up. The apocalypse case requires AI recoveries collapsing to 20%, no loan sellability, and banks refusing forbearance — simultaneously. Possible; not base case.

9. What makes this thesis wrong?
Every trade thesis needs an honest bull case for the other side. Here are the scenarios that would invalidate the short thesis and strengthen the long-quality case:

Bull scenario 1 — Hormuz reopens fast
Peace negotiations succeed within weeks. Brent falls back to $75. Fed returns to two-cut path. SOFR drops 50–75bp. Floating-rate borrowers get meaningful relief. ICR rebounds above 2.0×. Software default rates stay below 5%. The 25% NAV discount on OBDC closes to 10%. All alt manager stocks bounce 20–30%.

Bull scenario 2 — AI earnings vindicate the boom
Hyperscaler revenue beats consensus in Q1/Q2 earnings. Enterprise SaaS companies show evidence of AI-augmentation (selling AI tools built on their platforms) rather than disruption. Private credit software defaults stay in the 3–5% range. The "25% of portfolios exposed to AI disruption" narrative is reframed as "25% of portfolios exposed to AI upside."

Bull scenario 3 — Marks hold and Q1 filings are clean
May 2026 BDC filings show ICR stable at 2.0×+ and PIK income below 8%. The 90-day reporting lag captures Q1 2026 — the first marks post-all-three-shocks — and they show resilience. Sentiment-driven redemptions normalize. Institutional capital re-enters quality BDCs at discount. ARCC re-rates from 10% discount to premium, BXSL similarly.

Bull scenario 4 — Forbearance and bank patience
Chernenko/Scharfstein show that if banks exercise forbearance when BDCs hit technical covenant defaults, almost all funds cure within the stress period. The Fed and OCC quietly encourage forbearance. The 20–35% technical-default scenario resolves without realized losses. The system absorbs the stress slowly rather than liquidating rapidly.

The important pattern: all four bull scenarios depend on the Hormuz reopening or rate stabilization. Every single positive scenario for private credit is linked to the same geopolitical binary. That concentration of scenario dependency in one geopolitical event is itself a risk — it means the trade is really a leveraged bet on Middle East peace, with the private credit thesis layered on top.

