12. Glossary of key terms
ABF (Asset-Backed Finance)
Private credit loans backed by hard assets (aircraft, data centres, mortgages, auto loans) rather than corporate cash flows. Structurally safer in a downturn because collateral can be sold.
Amortised cost accounting
Recording assets at their original purchase price adjusted for amortisation, not current market value. Insurance companies use this — allowing them to avoid marking private credit losses to market.
ARR (Annual Recurring Revenue)
Total predictable annual subscription revenue. Private credit funds used ARR as a lending basis ("we'll lend 3× ARR") rather than EBITDA during 2020–2022. This was aggressive underwriting.
BSL (Broadly Syndicated Loans)
Large corporate loans originated by banks and sold to many institutional investors. The public equivalent of private credit direct lending. BSL market is ~$1.3T and has a functioning secondary market.
Carry cost
The ongoing cost of holding a derivative position. Buying CDX protection at 380bp means paying 3.8%/year — expensive if spreads don't widen further.
CLO (Collateralised Loan Obligation)
A structured vehicle that packages loans into tranches with different risk/return profiles. Used by private credit to raise capital against existing portfolios. Key source of demand for private credit loans.
Covenant
A contractual restriction on the borrower. "Maintenance covenant" = the borrower must maintain certain financial ratios (ICR, leverage) at all times. "Covenant-lite" = fewer such restrictions. 2021–2022 vintages were heavily covenant-lite.
Drawdown fund
A traditional private credit fund where LP capital is called and locked up for 7–10 years. Not subject to redemption gates because there's nothing to redeem — your money is committed until the fund winds down.
EBITDA
Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation and Amortisation. The primary measure of a private company's operating cash generation used in credit underwriting.
Financial ouroboros
A self-referential financial system where participants simultaneously invest in, borrow from, and sell to each other — inflating valuations without external demand validation. Applied to AI sector circular financing.
LBO (Leveraged Buyout)
Acquisition of a company using primarily debt (often 5–6× EBITDA). Private equity firms use LBOs heavily, and private credit funds are the primary debt provider. PE dry powder ($2.7T) creates demand for private credit.
LCR (Liquidity Coverage Ratio)
Basel III rule requiring banks to hold enough liquid assets to survive a 30-day stress event. Made bank middle-market lending expensive, driving borrowers to private credit. Currently under reform.
LME (Liability Management Exercise)
A restructuring short of formal default — debt-for-equity exchanges, maturity extensions, PIK toggles. The "true" default rate (including LMEs) is ~5% vs. the reported 2%.
NAV premium/discount
If NAV = $15/share and stock trades at $11, the discount is 27%. This discount implies the market thinks the loans are worth less than stated, or demands a liquidity premium for holding an illiquid vehicle, or both.
Non-accrual
A loan where the BDC has stopped accruing interest income because the borrower can't pay. Publicly disclosed quarterly. Non-accrual rate is a leading indicator of eventual write-offs.
SaaS (Software as a Service)
Subscription-based software delivered over the internet. Characterised by recurring revenue and high switching costs — the features that made SaaS companies attractive private credit borrowers.
